Introduction

This project is the datamining analysis on the RMS Titanic dataset.

The Titanic was a ship that attempted to sailed with passengers from Southampton, England to New York, USA. The RMS Titanic did not complete its voyage as it hit an iceberg and sank to the bottom of the Atlantic Ocean on April 15, 1912.

The following algoritms will be applied to the Titanic dataset.

Classification Algorithms:

  • Decision Tree Algorithm
  • Naïve Bayes
  • K-Nearest Neighbor
  • Logistic Regression
  • SVM Classification
  • Kernel SVM
  • Random Forest Classification

Regression Algoritihms:

  • Linear Regression
  • K-Nearest Neighbor
  • SVM Regression
  • Kernel SVM


In this exercise we will try to determine the following:

Which of the classification models and regression models used performed the best in predicting the probability of survival or non-survival from the Titanic?

Did any one or more features play a contributing factor in the probability of survival?

Data Summary

The Titanic dataset was taken from the following source: https://data.world/nrippner/titanic-disaster-dataset

As well, the description, summary and features below have been taken directly from the same source.

Description¶

Classic dataset on Titanic disaster used often for data mining tutorials and demonstrations

Summary¶

This is a classic dataset used in many data mining tutorials and demos -- perfect for getting started with exploratory analysis and building binary classification models to predict survival.

Data covers passengers only, not crew.

Features¶

  1. survival - Survival (0 = No; 1 = Yes)
  2. class - Passenger Class (1 = 1st; 2 = 2nd; 3 = 3rd)
  3. name - Name
  4. sex - Sex
  5. age - Age
  6. sibsp - Number of Siblings/Spouses Aboard
  7. parch - Number of Parents/Children Aboard
  8. ticket - Ticket Number
  9. fare - Passenger Fare
  10. cabin - Cabin
  11. embarked - Port of Embarkation (C = Cherbourg; Q = Queenstown; S = Southampton)
  12. boat - Lifeboat (if survived)
  13. body - Body number (if did not survive and body was recovered)

# as there is a large range of ages, we'll divide the ages into groups which may be easier to work with. 
data.insert(3, 'ageGroup', 0.0)

for item in data:
   # item['ageGroup'] = data['ageGroup'].astype(float)
    data.loc[ data['age'] <= 11, 'ageGroup'] = 0.0
    data.loc[(data['age'] > 11) & (data['age'] <= 19), 'ageGroup'] = 1.0
    data.loc[(data['age'] > 19) & (data['age'] <= 29), 'ageGroup'] = 2.0
    data.loc[(data['age'] > 29) & (data['age'] <= 39), 'ageGroup'] = 3.0
    data.loc[(data['age'] > 39) & (data['age'] <= 49), 'ageGroup'] = 4.0
    data.loc[(data['age'] > 49) & (data['age'] <= 59), 'ageGroup'] = 5.0
    data.loc[(data['age'] > 59) & (data['age'] <= 69), 'ageGroup'] = 6.0
    data.loc[(data['age'] > 69) & (data['age'] <= 79), 'ageGroup'] = 7.0
    data.loc[(data['age'] > 79) & (data['age'] <= 99), 'ageGroup'] = 8.0

K-Means Clustering¶

We will choose the age and boat column as the features to use in performing the KMean algorithm. These two features were arbitrarily chosen and there is no evidence to support the selection of these two features over a different pair of features.

In [44]:
# allocate data to X and y variables.  
Xk = data.loc[:, ['age','boat']].to_numpy()
y = np.array(data['survived'])
In [45]:
# import KMeans
from sklearn.cluster import KMeans


We will begin by using the Elbow Method to determine the optimal number of clusters. The code below can be found at the following source: https://medium.com/@michellibelly/k-means-clustering-for-analysis-of-heart-disease-c2c6f75927e0

In [46]:
# run the elbow method code
sse = []
list_k = list(range(1, 10))

for k in list_k:
    km = KMeans(n_clusters=k)
    km.fit(Xk)
    sse.append(km.inertia_)

# plot sse against k
plt.figure(figsize=(6, 6))
plt.plot(list_k, sse, '-o')
plt.xlabel(r'Number of clusters *k*')
plt.ylabel('Inertia');


From the Elbow method, it appears the optimal number of clusters to use is 3. However, because our target has two outcomes we will use run K-means with clusters of 2.

In [47]:
# create the K-Means object with n_cluster = 2 and fit the model
kmeansModel = KMeans(n_clusters=2)
kmeansModel.fit(Xk)

From the visualization of the K-Means clusters we can see from the prediction that there is a higher probability for younger passengers to get to a boat in an effort to try to increase their chances of survival.

We will apply the K-Means model to the original data to see if the predicted clusters are consistent with the actual clusters.

In [51]:
# apply K-means to the original data
y = [data['survived']]
plt.scatter(Xk[:,0],Xk[:,1],c=y,cmap='rainbow')
plt.title("Actual Clusters")
plt.xlabel('age')
plt.ylabel('boat')
plt.show()

By visual inspection the predicted clusters appear to be consitent with the actual clusters.

We can check the predicted data points one by one against the actual data points to determine the accuracy of the K-Means algorithm. To do so, we will use the code below which came from the following internet resource: https://t-magic.github.io/HRDS/Clustering/Clustering+using+K-Means+with+Titanic+Dataset.html.

From the discussion in the referenced source, "the group that is survivors might be a 0 or a 1, depending on a degree of randomness". That disussion concluded that an accuracy of 30% and 70% means that the k-means model is 70% accurate.

In [52]:
# check the accuracy of our k-means algorithm
y = np.array(data['survived'])
correct = 0
for i in range(len(Xk)):
    predict_me = np.array(Xk[i].astype(float))
    predict_me = predict_me.reshape(-1, len(predict_me))
    prediction = kmeansModel.predict(predict_me)
    if prediction[0] == y[i]:
        correct += 1

print(correct/len(Xk))

0.3330786860198625


It appears that our K-Means algorithm is 67% accurate.

Hierarchical Clustering¶

In the exploratory analysis using hierarchical clustering, there are no clear justifications that would lead us to choose one linkage criteria over the other. Thus, we will run the algorithm with the following linkage criterium: complete, single and average, and examine the resulting visualizations.

In [53]:
# import the hierarchial cluster library
from scipy.cluster.hierarchy import linkage, dendrogram
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
# remove the survived column from the DataFrame
outcomes = list(data['survived'])
samples = data.values
In [54]:
# perform hierarchical clustering on samples using the linkage() function with the method='complete' keyword argument. Assign the result to mergings
mergings = linkage(samples, method='complete')

Feature Engineering and PCA Dimension Reduction

Our correlation matrix showed us that the features are mostly independent. We will now attempt to determine to what extent did any of the features play in the survival probalilty of the passengers on the Titanic.

To ascertain what features are non-important, we will use Recursive Feature Elimination with estimators: Logistic Regression, Random Forest and Decision Tree. We will then use Recursive Feature Elimination followed by PCA Dimension Reduction.

Classification Algorithms¶

We will run our classification algorithms based on the optimal features from the RFECV using the logistic regression estimator, then the RFECV with the random forest estimator, followed by RFECV with the decision tree estimator, RFE, PCA with component = 5 and PCA with component = 1. We will then compare the results of the algorithms to determine which produced the best results. While we will compare a number of scoring metrics, we will use the accuracy score as the basis for determining which algorithm and, its associated feature selections, performed the best.

The classification algoritms that we will consider are as follows:

  1. Decision Tree Algorithm
  2. Naïve Bayes
  3. K-Nearest Neighbor
  4. Logistic Regression
  5. SVM Classification
  6. Kernel SVM
  7. Random Forest Classification

We will evaluate the accuracy of each model by applying K-fold Cross Validation to the model.

We begin by creating a series of functions that when called will run the required algorithms.

Create functions to define the classification and regression models/algorithms¶

In [101]:
# function that imports the algorithm classifier and creates the classifier object
def getModelObject(model):
    if(model == "Decision Tree"):
        # Decision Tree - we will use entropy to calculate the information gain
        from sklearn.tree import DecisionTreeClassifier
        # Create an instance of the classifier and fit the data to the model
        dtree = DecisionTreeClassifier(criterion='entropy')
        return dtree
    
    if(model == "Naives Bayes"):
        #import Naives Bayes, create the Naives Bayes object and fit the model
        from sklearn.naive_bayes import GaussianNB
        nb_clf = GaussianNB()
        return nb_clf
    
    if(model == "KNeighbor Classification"):
        from sklearn.neighbors import KNeighborsClassifier
        knn = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors = 3)
        #fit the model
        return knn
    
    if(model == "Logistic Regression"):
        from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression
        logreg = LogisticRegression(C=1.0, class_weight=None, dual=False, fit_intercept=True,
          intercept_scaling=1, max_iter=500, multi_class='ovr', n_jobs=1,
          penalty='l2', random_state=None, solver='liblinear', tol=0.0001,
          verbose=0, warm_start=False)
        return logreg
    
    if(model == "Random Forest"):
        from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier
        rfc = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=600)
        return rfc
    
    if(model == "SVM Classifcation"):
        #import SVM and create a SVM object
        from sklearn import svm
        cl_svm = svm.SVC()
        return cl_svm
    
    if(model == "Kernel SVM Classification"):
        #import SVC from SVM and create a SVC object
        from sklearn import svm
        from sklearn.svm import SVC
        ksvmCl = SVC(kernel = 'linear', random_state = 0)
        return ksvmCl
    
    if(model == "Linear Regression"):
        #import linear regression and create a linear regression object
        from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression
        linreg = LinearRegression()
        return linreg
    
    if(model == "KNeighbor Regression"):
        #import KNN regression and create a KNN regression object
        from sklearn.neighbors import KNeighborsRegressor
        regknn = KNeighborsRegressor(n_neighbors=2)
        return regknn
    
    if(model == "SVM Regression"):
        #import SVM regression and create a SVM regression object
        from sklearn import svm
        rSvm = svm.SVR()
        return rSvm
    
    if(model == "Kernel SVM Regression"):
        #import Kernel SVM regression and create a Kernel SVM regression object
        from sklearn.svm import SVR
        kRegSvm = SVR(kernel = 'rbf',gamma='auto')
        return kRegSvm


    
        
# function that runs the Classification Algorithms and makes the predictions
def runClassModel(model, X, y):
    # split X and y into training and testing sets
    from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
    X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, random_state=0)
    
    # get the calssifier object
    classifier = getModelObject(model)
    if(model == "SVM Kernel Classification"):
        # Feature scaling
        from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler
        sc = StandardScaler()
        X_train = sc.fit_transform(X_train)
        X_test = sc.transform(X_test)
        # fit the model
        classifier.fit(X_train, y_train)
        #make class the predictions with the testing set
        predictions = classifier.predict(X_test)
        predictions = sc.inverse_transform(X_test)
        return predictions
    else:   
        # fit the model
        classifier.fit(X_train, y_train)
        #make the class predictions for the testing set
        predictions = classifier.predict(X_test)
        return predictions
    
   
        
                
# function that runs the Regression Algorithms and makes the predictions
def runRegModel(model, X, y):
    # split X and y into training and testing sets
    from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
    X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, random_state=0)
    
    # get the calssifier object
    classifier = getModelObject(model)
    # fit the model
    classifier.fit(X_train, y_train)
    # make prediction from the model
    predictions = classifier.predict(X_test)
    
    # print the intercept and coefficients
    if(model == "Linear Regression"):
        print(" Linear Regression intercept and coefficient:\n\n")
        print(classifier.intercept_)
        print(classifier.coef_)
        print("\n")
        # pair the feature names with the coefficients
        pd.DataFrame(classifier.coef_, X.columns, columns = ['Coeff'])
    
    return predictions

# function that calculates and prints the results from the classification algortihms
def modelResults(model, predictions, y_test):
    from sklearn.metrics import classification_report,confusion_matrix
    print(model + " Confusion Matrix:")
    print(confusion_matrix(y_test,predictions))
    
    # format confusion matrix
    faceLabels = ['Not Survived (0)','Survived (1)']
    mat = confusion_matrix(y_test,predictions)
    sns.heatmap(mat.T, square=True, annot=True, fmt='d', cbar=False,
            xticklabels = faceLabels, cmap="BuPu", linecolor='black', linewidths=1,
            yticklabels = faceLabels)
    plt.xlabel('true label')
    plt.ylabel('predicted label');
    plt.show()
    print("\n")
    print("\n")
    print(model + " Classification Report:")
    print(classification_report(y_test,predictions))
    print("\n")
    print("\n")
    
# function that calculates and prints the results from the regression algortihms
def regModelResults(model, predictions, y_test):
    from sklearn import metrics
    from sklearn.metrics import r2_score
    
    # calculate MAE, MSE, RMSE
    print(model + " Error Calculations:\n")
    mae = metrics.mean_absolute_error(y_test, predictions)
    mse = metrics.mean_squared_error(y_test, predictions)
    rmse = np.sqrt(metrics.mean_squared_error(y_test, predictions))
    variance = r2_score(y_test, predictions)

    # print the results
    print(model + ' Variance score: %.2f' % variance)
    print(model + " MAE: : %.2f" % mae)
    print(model + " MSE: : %.2f" % mse)
    print(model + " RMSE: : %.2f" % rmse)
    print("\n")

# function to evaluate the performance of the classification models using 10-fold cross validation
def evalClassModels(modelList):
    from matplotlib import pyplot
    from numpy import mean
    from numpy import std
    
    # declare variables to hold scores
    results, modelNames = list(), list()
    
    print("Mean accuracy score of classification models using 10-fold Cross-Validation:\n")
    
    for item in modelList:
        # get model classifier
        classifier = getModelObject(item)
    
        # 10-fold cross-validation 
        from sklearn.model_selection import cross_val_score
        scores = cross_val_score(classifier, X, y, cv=10, scoring='accuracy')
        #add score to results list
        results.append(scores)
        modelNames.append(item)
        print('%s:  Mean-%.3f   Standard Deviation-(%.3f)' % (item, mean(scores), std(scores))) #Source: https://machinelearningmastery.com/rfe-feature-selection-in-python/

    # plot model performance for comparison. Code source: https://machinelearningmastery.com/rfe-feature-selection-in-python/
    plt.figure(figsize=(10,6))
    plt.boxplot(results, labels=modelNames, showmeans=True)
    plt.xticks(rotation=45)
    plt.title("Evaluation of Classification Models using 10-Fold Cross Evaluation")
    plt.show() 
    

# function to evaluate performance of the regression models/algorithms using 10-fold cross validation
def evalRegModels(regModelList):
    from sklearn.model_selection import cross_val_score
    from numpy import mean
    
    #declare variables to hold scores
    regMseResults, regRMSEResults, regModelNames = list(), list(), list()
    
    print("Regression Model Metrics:\n")
    count = 0
    for item in regModelList:
        #get model classifier
        classifier = getModelObject(item)

        # 10-fold cross-validation with Linear Regression
        regScore = cross_val_score(classifier, X, y, cv=10, scoring='neg_mean_squared_error')
        mean_mse = -regScore.mean()
        regMseResults.append(mean_mse)
        regModelNames.append(item)
        # convert from MSE to RMSE
        mean_rmse = np.sqrt(mean_mse.mean())
        regRMSEResults.append(mean_rmse)

        #print results
        print("K-fold " + item + "MSE: %.2f" % mean_mse)
        print("K-fold " + item + "RMSE: %.2f" % mean_rmse)
        print("\n")

# function to call and runs the classification algorithms and display model results when called
def callClassFunctions(X, y):
    import time
    #define Classification model variables
    DT = "Decision Tree"
    NB = "Naives Bayes"
    KNN = "KNeighbor Classification"
    LOGR = "Logistic Regression"
    RF = "Random Forest"
    SVMC = "SVM Classifcation"
    K_SVMC = "Kernel SVM Classification"

    dt_pred = runClassModel(DT, X, y)
    modelResults(DT, dt_pred, y_test)
    time.sleep(5)
    nb_pred = runClassModel(NB, X, y)
    modelResults(NB, nb_pred, y_test)
    time.sleep(5)
    knn_pred = runClassModel(KNN, X, y)
    modelResults(KNN, knn_pred, y_test)
    time.sleep(5)
    logr_pred = runClassModel(LOGR, X, y)
    modelResults(LOGR, logr_pred, y_test)
    time.sleep(5)
    rf_pred = runClassModel(RF, X, y)
    modelResults(RF, rf_pred, y_test)
    time.sleep(15)
    cl_svm_pred = runClassModel(SVMC, X, y)
    modelResults(SVMC, cl_svm_pred, y_test)
    time.sleep(5)
    ksvm_pred = runClassModel(K_SVMC, X, y)
    modelResults(K_SVMC, ksvm_pred, y_test)
    time.sleep(5)

Concluding Evaluation of Classification Algorithms¶


Of the classification algorithms, the training models based on PCA dimension 1 produced the most accurate results and therefore it is concluded that PCA dimension 1 is the best option for dimension reduction. From those training algorithm SVM produed the best accuracy. Thus, it is concluded that SVM is the best performing algorithm.

From the training algorithms based on RFECV and RFE, we were not able to conclude what were the best features that would increase the probility of survival. Clearly, whether one had a lifeboat was a factor, but also sex, class, embarked and siblings had an impact.

Regression Algorithms¶

We will run our regression algorithms based on the optimal features from the RFECV using the logistic regression estimator, then the RFECV with the random forest estimator, followed by RFECV with the decision tree estimator, RFE, PCA with component = 5 and PCA with component = 1. We will then compare the results of the algorithm to determine which produced the best results. While we will compare a number of scoring metrics, we will use the MSE score as the basis for determining which algorithm and, its associated feature selections, performed the best.

The regression algorithms that we will consider are as follows:

  1. Linear Regression
  2. K-Nearest Neighbor
  3. SVM Regression
  4. Kernel SVM

We will evaluate the accuracy of the MSE and RMSE of each model by applying K-fold Cross Validation to the model.

Concluding Evaluation of Regression Algorithms¶


Of the regression algorithms, the Linear Regression training models based on RFECV with Random Forest or Decision Tree performed the best with a 29% MSE. However, the test of the accuracy was high with at 20%. Therefore it is concluded that Random Forest and Decision Tree are both equally the best options for feature selection. Linear Regression consitently scored the lowest MSE in all cases. Thus,it is concluded that Linear Regression is the best performing algorithm.

From the training algorithms based on RFECV it was determined that having a lifeboat is the most optimal feature to impact the probabilty of survival or non-survival on the Titanic.

Final Conclusion¶

In conclusion, PCA dimension 1 produced the most accurate results in the classification algorithms. It performed better than the RFECV and RFE feature selection. Therefore, it is concluded that PCA dimension 1 is the best option for dimension reduction.

From those training classification algorithms SVM produced the best accuracy. Thus, it is concluded that SVM is the best performing algorithm.

In the regression algorithms, Linear Regression was the best performing algorithm. RFECV with Random Forest or Decision Tree both produced the most accurate results for feature selection and dimension reduction. The most optimal feature to impact the probabilty of survival or non-survival on the Titanic was having a lifeboat.
